  "prompt": "What are time zones?",
  "response": "Time zones are regions of the Earth that have adopted the same standard time for legal, commercial, and social purposes. Essentially, they're a system to standardize time across different longitudes, because when it's noon in one place, it's not noon everywhere else due to the Earth's rotation.\n\nHere's a breakdown of the key aspects:\n\n*   **Based on Longitude:** The Earth is divided into 360 degrees of longitude. Ideally, each 15 degrees of longitude would correspond to one hour of time difference (360 degrees / 24 hours = 15 degrees/hour).\n\n*   **Coordinated Universal Time (UTC):**  This is the primary time standard by which the world regulates clocks and time.  It's essentially the successor to Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), but is based on atomic clocks rather than astronomical observations. Time zones are typically defined by their offset from UTC. For example, Eastern Standard Time (EST) is UTC-5.\n\n*   **Standard Time vs. Daylight Saving Time:** Most time zones observe standard time for part of the year. Many regions then switch to daylight saving time (DST) during the spring and summer, advancing clocks by an hour to make better use of daylight.\n\n*   **Why Time Zones are Necessary:**\n    *   **Consistency:** Without time zones, every location would operate on its own local solar time. This would make scheduling travel, conducting business, and even coordinating communication extremely difficult.\n    *   **Daylight Hours:** Time zones help ensure that most locations have daylight hours roughly aligned with typical waking hours.\n    *   **Avoiding Confusion:** Imagine if nearby cities had significant time differences; it would be confusing for residents, businesses, and travelers.\n\n*   **Irregularities:** The actual time zone boundaries are not always strictly aligned with lines of longitude. They are often adjusted to follow political borders, administrative divisions, or geographical features. This is why you'll see time zones that aren't exactly an hour apart (like Nepal Standard Time, which is UTC+5:45).\n\nIn summary, time zones are an essential global system for standardizing time across the world. They provide consistency, facilitate communication and travel, and help align daylight hours with daily activities. They are based on the Earth's rotation and longitude but are often adjusted for practical and political considerations.\n",
